
Submission Documentation for Builders

The submit code handles submissions for:
  Bugs
  Typos
  Ideas
  Emotes
  Areas
  Unique Objects
  Mudlib Changes
  Guild Changes



BUG/TYPO/IDEA

  Bug/Typo/Idea submissions are done via the existing commands.  Bugs
  will no longer report to a log file.  They will exist in the
  submission daemon.  To look at the list of bugs, you will have to 
  do the following:

    listtable <bug|typo|idea> [name]

  If a bug, typo, or idea has been assigned to you for coding, you may
  be interested to list all of them assigned to you:

    listassigned <bug|typo|idea>

  This will list the bugs, ideas and typos for your area.  You can also
  leave off the name arguement and see a list of these for the entire
  mud.  Optional arguements will be the area subdirectory name:

    listtable bug darkwind
    listtable bug necro

  These will list bugs for the domain of darkwind, and those reported
  in the necro guild rooms.

  To list a specific bug, you will have to note the request number of
  the submission and then do:

    lst bug <request number>

  You will notice room for code, content and balance reviews for all
  submissions.  This won't be necessary for normal bug and typo
  submissions.  If they're in your area, you have permission to fix 
  the issue, and then get a balance member to close the submission for
  you.

  If you want to implement a new idea for your area, you will have to 
  resubmit the code that has changed.  This is discussed in detail,
  later.  The idea submissions are just meant to give you ideas about
  your area.

  Lots of times players submit things that are really mudlib issues, 
  and the bug will automatically be reported as a bug in an area.  If
  you notice a submission that isn't meant to be in regards to your
  area, you should mudmail a balance member, and we'll be happy to
  change the submission as appropriate.

  You also have the ability to respond to a bug, typo and idea
  submission (only these three.)  You can enter some information that 
  may help the player understand why something is coded in a particular
  fashion, or you may ask for more information.

    respond <bug|typo|idea> <request number>

  When you do close one of these submissions, a mudmail is sent to
  the submitter, saying:

    Thanks for your <bug|typo|idea> submission.  The submission has been
    closed, and the issue has been resolved.

    -<Name of Person who closed the submission>

  Note:  If you need more information about a submission, you can use 
  the respond command to mail the player.  They can then, in turn use
  the editbug, edittypo, editidea, or editemote commands to add more
  information.  If the submission is assigned to anyone, when the player
  updates it, then person to whom its assigned, will receive mudmail.



How do I submit things for approval?

  You use the submit command:

    submit <area|unique|lib|guild|emote> <Subject>



Oops!  I meant to say something else in my submission.  Can I edit it?

  Sure.  Use the command:

    editsub <area|unique|lib|guild|emote> <Subject>



How long does this take?

  The submission itself is obviously very quick.
  Depending on the load of the balance team, usually submissions are at
  least looked at, within a week.  By the time the submission is reviewed
  and the appropriate fixes are made, the entire process can take up
  to a month, for an area submission.



How can I see the status of my submisson?

  You can see your submission in table format:

    listtable <area|unique|lib|guild|emote> <your name>

  If a review has been posted, or if you want to check if there are 
  reviews pending that you haven't read, then notice the status in
  the output.  If the status says "Respond" then your response is
  more current than the review.  If it says "Reviewed" then the review
  is most current.



How do I see the review of my submission?

  listreview <area|unique|lib|guild|emote> <request number> [review type]
  
  To list just a specific review, add the review type to that command.

  You can also list your responses with the listresponse command.



A review has been posted, and I've made the changes.  Now what?

  You should add a response to the review, indicating what changes you
  have made:

    respondrev <area|unique|lib|guild|emote> <request number>
               <code|content|balance>



What happens when my submission is approved?

  An implementor can help you get your submission put into the game, as
  appropriate.

